==> Message Queues
	
	- we have two services Job service and Review Service and they are communicating
	- If a review service is down, in that case job service won't be able to communicate with Review service, we will get error
	- The communication between Job and review service is synchronous, because of that there is dependency in architecture i.e. tight coupling
	- How to decouple this communication 
	
	- Here Message Queue comes in picture for asynchronous communication which will provide us loose coupling
	- Message from Job service will left in Message Queue and later Review service will consume it if service is down. Message in  Message Queue will be there for a while
	- Need of Message Queue
		- Decoupling
		- Asynchronous communication - continues execution without waiting for immediate response , if job service does not need an immediate response and it just want to send some data to review service
										It can just send the data in Message Queue and just forget it.It is useful when certain operation takes time and are not that critical
										
		- Scalability 
		- Fault Tolerance - If Microservice is temprorily down then msg are stored in Message queue
		- Event Driven Architecture 
		- Time Decoupling
		
		- examples Kafka,RabbitMQ,Amazon SQS,ActiveMQ


==> RabbitMQ

	- Widely used open source Message Broker
	- Suppose we want to create Review along with Job, can be implemented with message queue
-> what we are going to build 

	- we have review service and company service
	- Review related info is stored in review service, reviews are belongs to companies
	- we can associate aggregate rating information, like whether company is rated 3*,4* or what
	- whenever new review is posted agreegate review should also change accordingly
	- Here review service will be producer and company service will be consumer
	
	
=> Installing RabbitMQ with docker

	- Command Line command
	
		docker run -d --name rabbitmq -p 5672:5672 -p 15672:15672 rabbitmq:3-management
		
		
	- docker-compose
	
		rabbitmq:
			image: rabbitmq:3-management
			container_name: rabbitmq
			ports:
				- 5672:5672  //this one is default rabbitmq port
				- 15672:15672 //this is for rabbitmq management - interface we can open in browser and manage //http://localhost:15672/#/
								//default username and password is guest
			networks:
				- job-app


	
	
	
		